    <!-- Tab content -->
    <div class="tab-content-wrapper">
      <!-- Overview -->
      <section id="tab-overview" class="tab-panel active">
        <h2>1. Project Overview</h2>
        <p>
          This project analyzes the classic US health insurance dataset to understand how factors like
          <strong>age, BMI, smoking status, children, and region</strong> relate to annual medical charges.
        </p>

        <h3>Objective</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Identify key drivers of high insurance charges.</li>
          <li>Visualize patterns and outliers in the dataset.</li>
          <li>Build simple regression models to predict charges and compare performance.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="meta-row">
          <span class="meta-pill">Tools: Python ¬∑ pandas ¬∑ matplotlib</span>
          <span class="meta-pill">Dataset: 1,338 rows ¬∑ 7 features</span>
          <span class="meta-pill">Type: Supervised regression</span>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Data -->
      <section id="tab-data" class="tab-panel">
        <h2>2. Input / Data</h2>
        <p>The dataset contains one row per insurance policyholder with the following columns:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>age</strong> ‚Äì age of the primary beneficiary (18‚Äì64).</li>
          <li><strong>sex</strong> ‚Äì male / female.</li>
          <li><strong>bmi</strong> ‚Äì body mass index (kg/m¬≤).</li>
          <li><strong>children</strong> ‚Äì number of dependents covered by insurance.</li>
          <li><strong>smoker</strong> ‚Äì yes / no.</li>
          <li><strong>region</strong> ‚Äì northeast, northwest, southeast, southwest.</li>
          <li><strong>charges</strong> ‚Äì annual medical insurance charges (target variable).</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Data preparation</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Loaded the CSV and validated the shape and data types.</li>
          <li>Checked missing values (none in this dataset).</li>
          <li>Explored distributions for age, BMI, charges, and number of children.</li>
          <li>Created features for modelling (e.g., one-hot encoding for categorical variables).</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="note">
          Dataset source:
          <a class="code-link" href="https://github.com/ttna812/health_insurance_2023/blob/main/insurance.csv" target="_blank">
            insurance.csv on GitHub
          </a>
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- EDA -->
      <section id="tab-eda" class="tab-panel">
        <h2>3. Exploratory Data Analysis &amp; Charts</h2>
        <div class="two-cols">
          <div>
            <h3>BMI vs Charges (by smoking status)</h3>
            <p>
              There is a strong upward relationship between BMI and charges, especially for smokers. Many of the highest-cost
              cases come from high-BMI smokers.
            </p>
            <img src="health_insurance_charges_bmi.png" alt="BMI vs charges scatter plot" class="chart" />
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3>Age distribution</h3>
            <p>
              Most policyholders are between 20 and 55 years old, with a relatively uniform distribution across working age.
            </p>
            <img src="health_insurance_age_distribution.png" alt="Age distribution histogram" class="chart" />
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="two-cols">
          <div>
            <h3>Charges by smoking status</h3>
            <p>
              Smokers have much higher median and upper-quartile charges, confirming that smoking is one of the main drivers
              of cost.
            </p>
            <img src="health_insurance_smoker_charges.png" alt="Boxplot of charges by smoker" class="chart" />
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3>Average charges by region</h3>
            <p>
              Average charges are relatively similar across regions, suggesting region plays a smaller role compared to BMI,
              age, and smoking.
            </p>
            <img src="health_insurance_region_charges.png" alt="Average charges by region bar chart" class="chart" />
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="note">
          All charts are generated in Python using <code>matplotlib</code>. See the notebook tab for full code.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Models -->
      <section id="tab-models" class="tab-panel">
        <h2>4. Models &amp; Output</h2>
        <p>
          I experimented with several regression models to predict <strong>charges</strong> from the available features.
          The goal is not to build a production-ready model, but to compare baselines and understand which variables matter.
        </p>

        <h3>Models tested</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Linear Regression</li>
          <li>Regularized models: Ridge / Lasso / ElasticNet</li>
          <li>Tree-based models: Random Forest, Gradient Boosting, XGBoost / CatBoost (where applicable)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Example evaluation metrics</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>RMSE</strong> ‚Äì root mean squared error on the test set.</li>
          <li><strong>MAE</strong> ‚Äì mean absolute error (more robust to outliers).</li>
          <li><strong>R¬≤</strong> ‚Äì proportion of variance in charges explained by the model.</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="note">
          In general, tree-based models outperform simple linear models, especially due to non-linear effects in BMI and age
          and interactions with smoking.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Code -->
      <section id="tab-code" class="tab-panel">
        <h2>5. Notebook &amp; Code</h2>
        <p>
          All data cleaning, EDA, visualizations, and modelling are implemented in a Jupyter notebook.
          You can inspect the full workflow or reuse parts of the code.
        </p>

        <div class="code-link-row">
          <a class="code-link" href="https://github.com/ttna812/health_insurance_2023/blob/main/notebook_health.ipynb" target="_blank">
            üìì Open analysis notebook on GitHub
          </a>
          <a class="code-link" href="https://github.com/ttna812/health_insurance_2023" target="_blank">
            üêô View project repository
          </a>
          <a class="code-link" href="https://github.com/ttna812/health_insurance_2023/blob/main/insurance.csv" target="_blank">
            üìÇ Download dataset (CSV)
          </a>
        </div>

        <h3>Example steps in the notebook</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Load and inspect dataset, check for missing values and data types.</li>
          <li>Univariate distributions and summary statistics for each feature.</li>
          <li>Bivariate relationships (scatterplots, boxplots, grouped summaries).</li>
          <li>Feature engineering and encoding for modelling.</li>
          <li>Training multiple models and comparing metrics.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script>
    // Simple tab logic
    const tabs = document.querySelectorAll(".tab");
    const panels = document.querySelectorAll(".tab-panel");

    tabs.forEach((tab) => {
      tab.addEventListener("click", () => {
        const target = tab.getAttribute("data-tab");

        tabs.forEach((t) => t.classList.remove("active"));
        panels.forEach((p) => p.classList.remove("active"));

        tab.classList.add("active");
        document.getElementById(`tab-${target}`).classList.add("active");
      });
    });
  </script>
